    "output": "To add a silent 2-second intro to all MP3 files in a folder in one batch command, you can automate the process using a shell loop (e.g., bash) combined with ffmpeg. The approach is:\n\n- Generate 2 seconds of silent audio using the `anullsrc` filter.\n- Concatenate the silent audio with the original MP3 using the `concat` filter.\n- Export the result as a new file or overwrite the original (recommended to output to a new file to avoid data loss).\n- Loop over all `.mp3` files in the folder to process them sequentially.\n\nThis method avoids creating temporary silent files, keeps the operations in-memory, and preserves original audio parameters like sample rate and channel layout.\n\nHereâ€™s an example bash command you can run in the folder containing your MP3s. It creates new files with `_intro` appended before the extension:\n\n```bash\nfor f in *.mp3; do\n  ffmpeg -i \"$f\" -f lavfi -t 2 -i anullsrc=channel_layout=stereo:sample_rate=44100 \\\n  -filter_complex \"[1:a][0:a]concat=n=2:v=0:a=1[a]\" -map \"[a]\" -c:a libmp3lame -q:a 2 \"${f%.mp3}_intro.mp3\"\ndone\n```\n\nExplanation:\n\n- `-f lavfi -t 2 -i anullsrc=channel_layout=stereo:sample_rate=44100` generates 2 seconds of stereo silent audio at 44100 Hz.\n- `-filter_complex \"[1:a][0:a]concat=n=2:v=0:a=1[a]\"` concatenates silent audio ([1:a]) before the original audio ([0:a]).\n- `-map \"[a]\"` selects the concatenated output.\n- `-c:a libmp3lame -q:a 2` encodes audio with high-quality MP3 codec settings.\n- `${f%.mp3}_intro.mp3` outputs the new file, appending `_intro` to ensure originals are preserved.\n\nAssumptions:\n\n- Your MP3s are stereo with 44100 Hz sample rate or close; adjust `anullsrc` parameters if your MP3s use other layouts or rates.\n- You run this in a Unix-like shell environment.\n- You want to keep original files unchanged and save new ones with `_intro` suffix.\n\nIf you want to overwrite files, you could output directly to the same filename, but be cautious as it may cause data loss if interrupted.",
